<paragraph id="8BD536EDFFD16569FF43405BFE22C03C" blockId="21.[151,1436,318,1002]" box="[151,389,318,343]" pageId="21" pageNumber="22">
<typeStatus id="54D1884FFFD16569FF43405BFF68C03D" box="[151,207,319,343]" pageId="21" pageNumber="22">Type</typeStatus>
locality: 
<collectingCountry id="F37D767DFFD16569FEEC405AFE22C03C" box="[312,389,318,342]" name="United States of America" pageId="21" pageNumber="22">U.S.A.</collectingCountry>
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BD536EDFFD16569FF134005FD49C013" blockId="21.[151,1436,318,1002]" box="[199,750,353,377]" pageId="21" pageNumber="22">
Described by 
<bibRefCitation id="EFFB4B1CFFD16569FEB64006FDABC013" author="Munroe, E." box="[354,524,353,377]" pageId="21" pageNumber="22" refId="ref43251" refString="Munroe, E. (1972) Pyraloidea, Pyralidae (Part) The Moths of America north of Mexico. Fascile 13.1. 304 + xx pp., 24 pl." type="book" year="1972">Munroe (1972)</bibRefCitation>
and 
<bibRefCitation id="EFFB4B1CFFD16569FD974005FD4EC013" author="Shaffer, M." box="[579,745,353,377]" pageId="21" pageNumber="22" pagination="155 - 158" refId="ref43440" refString="Shaffer, M. (1968) Illustrated notes on Synclita obliteralis (Walker) and Euzophera bigella (Zeller), two species new to the British list. (Lepidoptera: Pyralidae). Entomologist's Gazette, 19, 155 - 158." type="journal article" year="1968">Shaffer (1968)</bibRefCitation>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BD536EDFFD16569FF1340E0FC66C34D" blockId="21.[151,1436,318,1002]" pageId="21" pageNumber="22">
Imago (Figs. 24, 25): Male wingspan 
<quantity id="4C929B08FFD16569FDB940E0FD78C0F6" box="[621,735,388,412]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.15" metricValueMax="1.3" metricValueMin="1.0" pageId="21" pageNumber="22" unit="mm" value="11.5" valueMax="13.0" valueMin="10.0">10–13mm</quantity>
. Head dark fuscous; labial palpus tufted, porrect, pale fuscous; antenna dull fuscous. Thorax dark fuscous. Forewing predominantly dark fuscous; pale subbasal fascia and a postmedian fascia mixed whitish, orange and fuscous; discal spot white, ringed dark fuscous; termen chequered white and dark fuscous. Hindwing dark fuscous; an orange tornal spot preceded by whitish scales. Legs fuscous, darker on joints. Abdomen dark fuscous, paler on edge of each segment.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BD536EDFFD16569FF134355FCCFC3E4" blockId="21.[151,1436,318,1002]" pageId="21" pageNumber="22">Male genitalia (Fig. 96): Uncus long, spatulate, slightly broader beneath apex, gnathos narrow 2/3 length of uncus, bearing a series of spines on the dorsal edge, valva simple; aedeagus fairly broad, bent near apex and bearing a thick cornutus, the apex being surrounded with spines.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BD536EDFFD16569FF1343FDFE58C3BE" blockId="21.[151,1436,318,1002]" pageId="21" pageNumber="22">Female genitalia (Fig. 146): Ostium wide, ostial chamber narrowing and then broadening into corpus bursae which bears sclerotised patches.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BD536EDFFD16569FF1343BAFC29C39C" blockId="21.[151,1436,318,1002]" box="[199,910,734,759]" pageId="21" pageNumber="22">Tympanal organs: Venulae widely separated, slightly divergent.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BD536EDFFD16569FF134265FC2BC273" blockId="21.[151,1436,318,1002]" box="[199,908,769,793]" pageId="21" pageNumber="22">Diagnosis: Distinguished by its lack of crosslines on the wings.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BD536EDFFD16569FF134240FA3DC251" blockId="21.[151,1436,318,1002]" box="[199,1434,804,828]" pageId="21" pageNumber="22">
Biology: Larva on a variety of aquatic plants, in the 
<collectingCountry id="F37D767DFFD16569FCC44240FCEFC256" box="[784,840,804,828]" name="United States of America" pageId="21" pageNumber="22">USA</collectingCountry>
recorded from 
<emphasis id="B91EEAFFFFD16569FC214240FACDC256" box="[1013,1386,804,828]" italics="true" pageId="21" pageNumber="22">
<taxonomicName id="4C6A4D6EFFD16569FC214240FBD7C256" box="[1013,1136,804,828]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Nymphaeaceae" genus="Nymphaea" kingdom="Plantae" order="Nymphaeales" pageId="21" pageNumber="22" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">Nymphaea</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName id="4C6A4D6EFFD16569FBAF4241FAB4C256" box="[1147,1299,805,828]" class="Liliopsida" family="Potamogetonaceae" genus="Potamogeton" kingdom="Plantae" order="Alismatales" pageId="21" pageNumber="22" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">Potamogeton</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName id="4C6A4D6EFFD16569FACA4241FACDC256" box="[1310,1386,805,828]" class="Liliopsida" family="Araceae" genus="Lemna" kingdom="Plantae" order="Alismatales" pageId="21" pageNumber="22" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">Lemna</taxonomicName>
</emphasis>
etc.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BD536EDFFD16569FF134222FF58C2EB" blockId="21.[151,1436,318,1002]" pageId="21" pageNumber="22">
Distribution: 
<collectingCountry id="F37D767DFFD16569FE8A4222FE54C234" box="[350,499,838,862]" name="South Africa" pageId="21" pageNumber="22">South Africa</collectingCountry>
, presumed to have been introduced, either accidentally or deliberately, from North America.
</paragraph>
